This started happening after I upgraded to 0.10.0 to fix the duplicate Model name issue I reported earlier. We discovered that we started getting errors such as 

`Type of value given to save() method is not a valid SQLALchemy declarative class. Item with index 0 and with value "`

Upon further debugging by looking at the instance of SQLClient via .models.values() we discovered an empty dictionary. I saw in the 0.10.0 change log that there was some kind of code change for this. I'm not sure if it's related to how we instantiate the base class but I've posted a bit of our code to help out.

database.py
```
from sqlservice import SQLClient
from orm import Model
from config import BaseConfig

config = {
    'SQL_DATABASE_URI': 'postgresql://{0}:{1}@{2}:{3}/{4}'.format(
        BaseConfig.DATABASE['DB_USER'], BaseConfig.DATABASE['DB_PASS'],
        BaseConfig.DATABASE['DB_SERVICE'], BaseConfig.DATABASE['DB_PORT'],
        BaseConfig.DATABASE['DB_NAME'])
}

db = SQLClient(config, model_class=Model)
```

orm.Model
```
import datetime

import sqlalchemy as sa

from sqlservice import declarative_base, ModelBase

from sqlalchemy import MetaData
from sqlalchemy.ext.declarative import declared_attr


meta = MetaData(naming_convention={
    "ix": 'ix_%(column_0_label)s',
    "uq": "uk_%(table_name)s_%(column_0_name)s",
    "ck": "ck_%(constraint_name)s",
    "fk": "fk_%(column_0_name)s_%(referred_table_name)s",
    "pk": "pk_%(table_name)s"
}, schema='public')

class MyCustomBase(ModelBase):
    @declared_attr
    def created_by(cls):
        return sa.Column(sa.SmallInteger, sa.ForeignKey('public.user.user_id'))

    @declared_attr
    def created_ts(cls):
        return sa.Column(sa.DateTime(timezone=False), nullable=False,
                         default=datetime.datetime.utcnow,
                         server_default=sa.func.now())

    @declared_attr
    def modified_by(cls):
        return sa.Column(sa.SmallInteger, sa.ForeignKey('public.user.user_id'))

    @declared_attr
    def modified_ts(cls):
        return sa.Column(sa.DateTime(timezone=False),
                         onupdate=datetime.datetime.utcnow,
                         server_onupdate=sa.func.now())


Model = declarative_base(MyCustomBase, metadata=meta)
```

Subsequent model files then import Model from orm.Model like so
```
import sqlalchemy as sa
from sqlalchemy.dialects.postgresql.json import JSON

from orm import Model

class User(Model):
    __tablename__ = 'user'

    user_id = sa.Column(sa.Integer, primary_key=True)
```

When I downgrade to 0.9.1, everything works as expected.

